    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-11T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-11T01:00:00-05:00" n="1567"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1567">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">780.022/6–1154: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1567<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Saudi Arabia (<persName corresp="#p_WG1"
                            type="from">Wadsworth</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1567fn1">Repeated to London and Dhahran.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-11T09:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 11, 1954—9 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>506. Re <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 347, June 7.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d1567fn2">Not printed, but see <ref target="#d1566fn2">footnote 2,
                                <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Since question of <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> resuming
                        exploration in disputed eastern area was first raised by <gloss
                            target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> in conversations with <persName
                            corresp="#p_OFW1">Ohliger</persName> last March I have sensed <gloss
                            target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss>’s policy attitudes increasingly
                        determined by following three primary considerations: <list>
                            <label>a.</label>
                            <item>Desire avoid involvement in boundary dispute between governments.
                                (A policy enunciated in writing to British following 1949 Stobart
                                incident.) This led to <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss>
                                taking basic position which it <pb facs="0911" n="2613"
                                    xml:id="pg_2613"/> still holds as matter of principle that
                                British companies should cease operation the disputed area during
                                arbitration.</item>
                            <label>b.</label>
                            <item>Desire maintain best possible relations with <gloss
                                    target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss>. This led <gloss
                                    target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> (when later it became clear
                                that British Government would not receive from position that British
                                companies must continue operations) to concur in <gloss
                                    target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> view that British and Saudi
                                positions might be equalized by resumption <gloss
                                    target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> explorations suspended in
                                1949 at <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> request.</item>
                            <label>c.</label>
                            <item>Desire protect its own interests in valuable oil reserves disputed
                                area a consideration rendered more acute by suspected Saudi intrigue
                                designed make deal with British whereby <gloss target="#t_SAG1"
                                    >SAG</gloss> would gain sovereignty over disputed area in return
                                for oil concession therein to British companies. This led <gloss
                                    target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> to implement specific Saudi
                                request by resuming operations in western part of area where it had
                                earlier sent exploration parties first in 1937–1938 and again
                                1948–1949.</item>
                        </list>
                        <gap/>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> states categorically “not taking
                        more initiative than previously indicated”.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WG1">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wadsworth</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
